# audit-rule-file.bnf — slay-format BNF metagrammar for n00b-audit
# rule files (`.bnf` rule-file format v2; WP-005).
#
# This metagrammar describes the audit-rule-file format that
# `src/audit/guidance.c` loads. The format is a plain-text file
# carrying file-level `@<directive>` metadata, one or more
# `@rule <id>` sections (each with its own per-rule directives),
# and embedded BNF productions interspersed between `@rule`
# markers.
#
# # Token shape (custom tokenizer in src/audit/rule_file_tokenizer.c)
#
# Lines are classified by their leading character (after any
# leading whitespace stripping for `INDENT_LINE`):
#
#   RULE_MARKER  — `@rule <id>` lines; emits the rule id as the
#                  token's text payload.
#   DIRECTIVE    — `@<word>` lines other than `@rule`; emits the
#                  directive name (without the `@`) as the
#                  token's text payload.
#   REST         — the trailing text of a `DIRECTIVE` line (the
#                  bytes after the directive word + one space,
#                  trimmed of trailing whitespace). Always
#                  emitted after a DIRECTIVE, even if empty.
#   INDENT_LINE  — a continuation line that begins with a space
#                  or tab. Emits the line content trimmed of
#                  the leading whitespace.
#   BNF_LINE     — any other non-empty line. The token's text
#                  is the entire line content (preserved
#                  verbatim so the BNF body is reconstructable
#                  via concatenation).
#   NEWLINE      — physical line terminator; appended after
#                  every line.
#
# Comments (`# ...`) and blank lines are skipped as trivia.
#
# # Two-pass loader design
#
# The metagrammar treats each rule's BNF body as opaque
# `BNF_LINE` tokens. The loader walks the parse tree to extract
# metadata + concatenates each rule's `BNF_LINE` contents into
# the rule's `bnf_fragment` field. The engine then loads each
# rule's `bnf_fragment` via slay's existing `n00b_bnf_load`
# (unchanged from the prior JSON-driven pipeline) — the BNF
# body is **never** re-parsed by this metagrammar.
#
# # Why this shape
#
# Slay's existing BNF tokenizer is incompatible with our
# directive-line shape (`@` carries different semantics, our
# metadata lines aren't BNF productions). So we register a
# dedicated `"audit_rule_file"` tokenizer that emits the
# coarse line-kind tokens above; the metagrammar below is
# straightforward to walk in the loader.

<file> ::= <file_meta> <rule_section>*

<file_meta> ::= <meta_field>*

<meta_field> ::= %DIRECTIVE %REST %NEWLINE <continuation>*

<continuation> ::= %INDENT_LINE %NEWLINE

<rule_section> ::= <rule_marker> <meta_field>* <bnf_body>

<rule_marker> ::= %RULE_MARKER %NEWLINE

<bnf_body> ::= <bnf_line>*

# A `<bnf_line>` is either an unindented body line (`%BNF_LINE`) or
# a continuation line that begins with whitespace (`%INDENT_LINE`).
# Indented lines arise inside slay's leveled `rewrite { ... }` blocks
# attached to productions (WP-007); the loader concatenates them into
# the rule's `bnf_fragment` so slay's BNF tokenizer sees the rewrite
# body as one contiguous span. Indented lines have their leading
# horizontal whitespace stripped by the audit-rule-file tokenizer,
# which is fine because slay's rewrite-block field parser also
# strips per-field whitespace.
<bnf_line> ::= %BNF_LINE %NEWLINE
<bnf_line> ::= %INDENT_LINE %NEWLINE
